[1] Jackals, alert, control, public debate
Date: Tue 2 Jan 2017
Source: MAKO News [in Hebrew, trans, summ, edited]
https://www.mako.co.il/news-israel/health-q1_2018/Article-53f125e6ef5b061004.htm


Rabies was discovered and lab-confirmed in 3 jackals found in the 3 kibbutz settlements Shluhot, Maoz Hayim, and Kfar Ruppin, situated in the [Bet-She'an area, north east [NE] Israel], the Ministry of Health [MoH] announced today [2 Jan 2018]. [Later, 2 more cases were lab confirmed. The locations of the 5 cases in jackals confirmed in northern Israel since 1 Jan 2018 are presented in a map, dated 2 Jan 2018, at http://www.moag.gov.il/vet/Yechidot/Machon/maabada_kalevet/airueim%20kalevet/Documents/mapa_kalevet_02.01.18.jpg]. The MoH emphasizes that anyone who has had contact, or whose animals had or suspected to have had contact with an infected or free-roaming animal should contact the nearest health office to consider preventive treatment.

The regional councils 'Valley of Springs' and 'Gilboah', in NE Israel, notified the Ministry of Agriculture: "In view of the continuing, unending outbreak and the emergency situation, we are obliged to rely only on ourselves; it has been decided at our last meeting to recruit and immediately put in action veterinarians, trappers, inspectors, and vehicles, as well as supply the volunteering agriculturists with weapons and increase field activities as prescribed by the worsening situation. This, on top of the actions already undertaken by the councils."

The government is concerned about the possible infection of people -- in particular children -- if the disease spreads into additional regions in central and southern Israel. The director general of the Ministry of Health has submitted to his counterpart in the Ministry of Agriculture a call to urgently apply measures in order to decrease the density of wildlife populations which are rabies vectors. "Any adequate measure should be applied, including controlled use of poisoning in defined areas and any other means if deemed necessary to prevent losing control."

Following the publication, minister of agriculture Ariel responded: "I have no intention of sanctioning poisoning as a means of rabies control; I have already rejected this possibility and there is no need for it." Nevertheless, his office was already preparing for the start of the poisoning.

Israel's Nature Protection Society expressed concern about the publication: "Poisoning methods have brought disaster to the Israeli fauna during the previous century, bringing many species to the brink of extinction and even to extinction, such as biblical vultures, Egyptian vultures [_Neophron percnopterus_], striped hyenas [_Hyaena hyaena_] and cinereous vultures [_Aegypius monachus_]. In addition, poisoning is not in state to solve the problem of the spread of rabies: this can be stopped by a combination of solutions: by stopping the unacceptable availability of food sources to wild animals from neglected garbage and waste; by vaccination of wildlife, livestock, and pets; by selective dilution of wild animals applied professionally by authorized specialists; by pet sterilization and neutering; and by the enforcement of existing laws and regulations concerning the maintenance of these animals."

[byline: Guy Varon]

